\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 26.          Antennaria}         Gaertner
\par 

\pard\f0\fs24\qc By G. Halliday
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28 Dioecious, usually tomentose perennial herbs, with basal leaf rosettes and erect, simple, leafy, flowering stems with a terminal cluster of 1-8(-12) shortly pedunculate, small capitula. Involucral bracts in several rows, erect in fruit. Receptacle flat, without scales. Female florets filiform-tubular; functionally male florets tubular; pappus-hairs in several rows, those of the functionally male florets conspicuously thickened above.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28   Sexual or apomictic; in the latter case often only the female plants are known. In the sexual species {\b 1} and {\b 5}, little taxonomic importance is usually attached to widely differing amounts of tomentum on the leaves; in the apomictic species {\b 3} and {\b 4} such variation appears to have a phytogeographical and cytological significance.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28   Short glandular hairs are usually present but are often concealed by the tomentum.
